In total, 130 (76%) of the 171 positive samples were positive for only one respiratory pathogen, 37 (22%) samples were positive for two pathogens and four (2%) were positive for three pathogens. HBoV was most frequently found associated with other pathogens in co-infections (21/34, 62%). Co-infections were also frequent with AdV and HCoV. By contrast, INF A and HRV/EV were mostly found in single infections (22% and 29%, respectively) (Table 2
). For each pathogen, we calculated the frequency of association with other pathogens. Differences between the expected and observed rates of co-infection may indicate preferential association or mutual exclusion. Overall, the associations observed were consistent with the prevalence of the partners in the population of pathogens, with the exception of INF A and HRV/EV, which appeared to be mutually exclusive (P
 = 6 × 10−4).
